    <text>
        <body>
            
            <div1 type="letter">
                
                <pb facs="nei.j4a.26c.74-75_0001"/>
                
                <fw type="curatorial">74</fw>
                
                <opener>
                    <salute>Dear Doctor Neihardt,</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>I was very happy to hear from you andthe<sic>and the</sic> article you sent has been very helpful. I am going to be in Chicago on business the end of the month and so I am planning to have my wife <del>I</del><add>j</add>oin me and we are going to fly to Columbia to visit you for a day. She is all excited about meeting you and I am very happy to have the opportunity to spend a day with you. If you write back that you will be home, we plant<sic>plan</sic> to fly to Columbia Saturday January 3rd and spend the whole afternoon <del>with you</del>. We wil<add>l</add> have to leave for Saint Louis that night but we'll have plenty of time to talk about the past<add>,</add> present and future. I wou<del>o</del><add>l</add>d appreciate if you let me know as soon as possible if you will be in Columbia because I will make my plane reservations.</p>
                
                <p>I know that this year has had great sadness for you but we are of the same philosphical<sic>philosophical</sic> mold and I am sure that it has not changed your outlook. Life has been kind to you in allowing you to do w<del>j</del><add>h</add>at you dreamed of. My life still consists of the dreams and you have been inspirational in giving me the feeling that dreams <del>t</del><add>d</add>o become actualities. I cannot wait until <del>I see you</del> Jan 3rd when my wife and you and I get together.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute>Sincerely</salute>
                    
                    <signed>Bob Leaf</signed>
                </closer>
                
            </div1>
            
            
